pi—not revealing their scholarly project or even their association with one another—groundbreaking Black scholar Allison Davis and his White co-authors, Burleigh and Mary Gardner, delivered an unprecedented examination of how race shaped nearly every aspect of twentieth-century life in the United States. Their analysis notably revealed the importance of caste and class to Black and White worldviews, and they anatomized the many ways those views are constructed, solidified, and reinforced. ​ This reissue of the 1965 abridged edition, with a new foreword from Pulitzer Prize winner Isabel Wilkerson—who acknowledges the book’s profound importance to her own work—proves that Deep South remains as relevant as ever, a crucial work on the concept of caste and how it continues to inform the myriad varieties of American inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAfrican AmericanszSouthern States. 0aSocial classeszSouthern States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aDavis, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Burleigh B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGardner, Mary R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWarner, W. Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilkerson, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226817996423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226817996/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles